The two essential parts.

Every correct recursive function has exactly two parts. The first is the base case — the condition under which the function stops calling itself and returns a direct answer. Without a base case, the function recurses forever until the call stack overflows. The second is the recursive case — the step where the function calls itself with a smaller or simpler version of the problem, moving toward the base case.

The key insight is that each recursive call must make progress toward the base case. If it does not, you have infinite recursion.

Consider factorial. Factorial of five is five times four times three times two times one — which equals one hundred and twenty. The base case is: if n is less than or equal to one, return one. The recursive case is: return n multiplied by factorial of n minus one. Notice how n minus one is strictly smaller than n — every call moves closer to the base case.
